---

# Loading States

Prefer:

* Skeleton cards
* Skeleton charts
* Placeholder avatars

Avoid:

* Large spinning loaders

---

# Accessibility

* Minimum text contrast: WCAG AA
* Keyboard navigation
* Visible focus states
* Alt text for images
* Don't rely only on color to communicate meaning
* Minimum touch target: 44×44px

---

# Responsive Design

## Desktop

Prioritize side-by-side comparisons and multi-column layouts.

## Tablet

Reduce columns while keeping charts readable.

## Mobile

Stack content vertically.

Move advanced statistics into collapsible sections.

Always keep important information above the fold.

---

# Design Checklist

Before shipping any screen, verify:

* Plenty of whitespace
* One primary action per section
* No overwhelming tables
* Numbers are easy to scan
* Visualizations support the data
* Consistent spacing
* Consistent typography
* Consistent colors
* Mobile-friendly layouts
* Accessible interactions

---

# Final Design Philosophy

A football statistics platform should help users understand the game—not make them work to decipher it.

Every screen should feel calm, spacious, and intentional. Statistics should reveal the story behind a player, team, or match through thoughtful hierarchy, meaningful visuals, and progressive disclosure. Casual fans should immediately grasp the key takeaways, while enthusiasts can seamlessly explore deeper analytics.

The guiding principle for every design decision is:

> **Insights first. Statistics second. Simplicity always.**
